topic.title: GPIO Pin Usage

section.p: This field uses two bits for each GPIO pin to specify its operating function.
section.note: GPIO pins 16-19 are not defined in the Switchtec device.
section.p: The GPIO pin 28-35, 49-59, and 107-109 are not available for PM8563, PM8562, PM85621, PM8553, PM8552, PM8551, PM8543, PM8542, PM8541, PM8533, PM8532 and PM8531 variants.

3.3V Tolerant I/Os only provide an Open-Drain Output and are not capable of driving high. A pull-up resistor must be added unless this signal is tied to ground.
GPIO Pin Initial state after RSTB is as follows:
GPIO [38, 41]: Pin Direction = Input; State = '0'
GPIO[40:39, 44:43, 46, 48, 81:76]: Pin Direction = Input, State = '1'
Remaining all GPIO Pin Direction = Output, State = HighZ

entry.p: 3.3V Tolerant I/O. Open-Drain Output only. A GPIO pin does not require a pull-up to support 3.3V logic when configured as an input. If a GPIO pin is configured as an output to drive 3.3V logic then a pull-up resistor is required

section.p: 1) If a block is used as a TWI bus, both SDA and SCL pins must be configured to TWI, otherwise neither of the pins in the block can be configured to TWI. The SRSTB pin can be re-purposed to any available function for that pin (i.e TWI_SRSTB[8] can be re-purposed to SGPIO_SDATAOUT[2] or GPIO[30]).
2) If a block is used as a UART bus, all 4 pins must be configured to UART, otherwise none of the pins in the block can be configured to UART.
3) If a block is used as a SGPIO bus, all 4 pins must be configured to SGPIO, otherwise none of the pins in this block can be configured to SGPIO.
4) TPIN and TPOUT can be re-purposed to any available signal of that GPIO.

5) If a block is used as a SPI bus, all pins except CSB0[1] and CSB1[1] must be configured to SPI, otherwise none of the pins in this block can be configured to SPI. The QSPI0 block must be used as the boot SPI. If CSB is not used by the SPI, it can be re-purposed to any available signal of that GPIO.
6) If the RMII/MII interface is used, all pins in Ethernet RMII/MII block must be configured to Ethernet, otherwise none of the pins in the RMII/MII block can be configured to Ethernet.

7) If a block is used as an LBI bus, all pins except DATA[8:15], A[1:23], CEB[0:3] must be configured to LBI, otherwise none of pins in this block can be configured to LBI. If DATA[8:15], A[1:23] and CEB[0:3] pins are not used by the LBI they can be re-purposed to any available signal of that GPIO. However, if it is used as an LBI bus, it also depends on the flash data mode (Byte/Word), capacity(address range) and Chip Select being attached.
7) A single pin function setting like GPIO, PWM and TACH_IN must not violate the guidelines in other blocks.
8) Bootstrap pins are only sampled at boot, after booting the related GPIO pins can be used for other function they are capable of.
9) GPIO[44:38] are dedicated to QSPI_0 in Switchtec.
